prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Direct detection of 850um continuum emission in z~5 LBGs
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note:
The aim of this science goal is to directly detect the continuum dust emission at 850um from a sample of photometrically-selected LBGs at z~5 based on our previous stacked 850um flux measurement from our SCUBA-2 observations.
We may also serendipitously detect [CII]158um in some of our sources, depending on the true redshift of each source, which will give us a spectroscopic redshift and CII flux for a subset of our z~5 LBG sample.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
We have chosen to centre our total 7.5 GHz of bandwidth (per polarization) at the suggested default frequency for Band 7 of 343.5GHz (which is a good match to the SCUBA2 bandpass) and to use dual polarization in continuum mode for the observations in order to maximise our sensitivity.
Our observations should also yield ~9 serendipitous [CII]158um detections, which can be obtained in this short integration time in the standard continuum mode (see e.g. Swinbank et al., 2012) with 31MHz channels (~27km/s), which is well-suited to detecting high-z galaxies. The expected peak line fluxes are ~3-10mJy for galaxies of similar IR luminosity to ours (Swinbank et al., 2012; Capak et al., 2015) which should be well detected (>3sigma) with an expected channel sensitivity of ~1.1mJy per 31MHz channel given our integration time. We will be able to sufficiently well-sample the CII line (assuming ~200 km/s FWHM) with ~7 spectral resolution elements in order to derive a flux and infer a redshift for the line emission.

Since our primary science goal is to detect the continuum emission of z=5 LBGs, we wish to use the most compact configuation which provides the most sensitive flux probe as well an angular resolution of ~1 arcsec at 850um (Band 7), which corresponds to a linear size of ~6.5kpc at z~5. This resolution will also enable us to search for potential multiplicity of LBGs in this faint IR luminosity regime (akin to that seen in the more luminous SMG population with ALMA at 1.5" resolution; Hodge et al., 2013).

We estimate the expected 850um fluxes of our targets based on our stacked flux measurement of 0.69 +/- 0.11 mJy for z~5 LBGs. Note that this stack has been updated for this proposal from our published measurement in Coppin et al. (2015) using the now-complete S2CLS UDS map reaching a nearly confusion-limited final depth of 0.9mJy, 1-sigma rms (Geach et al., in preparation). The stacked measurement from our 850um SCUBA2 study also dictates our wavelength choice here (as there are no assumptions to be made about the rather uncertain dust spectral index here, as would be needed if we were to observe in a different band).
Band 7 also provides the unique possibility of serendipitously detecting [CII]158um for our z~5 LBG sample, as CII is expected to be quite bright in these LBGs and detectable given our integration time and continuum depth goal (see e.g. Swinbank et al. 2012 who detected CII in even shorter integration times in Cycle 0 for galaxies with similar LIR~1d12 Lsun to our z~5 LBGs in Coppin et al., 2015).
Conservatively, we aim for a 1-sigma continuum sensitivity of 0.07 mJy, which would yield a >10-sigma detection for S850>0.7 mJy or >3-sigma for S850>0.2mJy (keeping in mind that that the quoted error on the stack is the (weighted) error on the mean and not the true scatter of measured fluxes, of course, which will be much noisier than this, hence our requested depth).
Since we obviously do not know a priori the precise 850um flux to expect for each LBG, we take the prudent approach here of aiming for a uniform rms sensitivity across the sample (rather than integrating down to a uniform S/N), keeping any biases in this survey to a minimum. Our proposed survey depth is based on our SCUBA-2 stacking result and sufficient to achieve an overall balance of good individual LBG detections needed to achieve our primary objectives in a reasonable amount of integration time per source.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose an ALMA direct detection experiment of 850um continuum emission in a large sample of 68 uniformly photometrically selected `typical' z~5 Lyman Break Galaxies (LBGs). LBGs and (more generally) `dropouts' have pushed our census of the SFRD out to z~10, albeit relying on very indirect estimates of the dust correction (employing a combination of the UV luminosity and the UV continuum slope). Of course, UV emission in dusty star-forming galaxies is known to be absorbed and re-radiated by dust - and studies measuring both the `unobscured' SFR (via the rest-frame UV) and `obscured' SFR (via the far-IR) have shown empirically that the dust extinction can be corrected reasonably well using local extinction laws up to z~2 but this is completely untested at z>2-3. Here we propose to provide a comparably precise measurement of this relationship at z=5 for the first time. Knowing the mean emission strength of the same 68 z~5 LBGs from our deep stacked SCUBA-2 observations, we will use ALMA Band 7 to determine both the actual dust attenuation, and the CII emission from up to ~13% of our sample.
